Absolutelyyou can mirror the entire directory tree to R2 (keeping every sub-folder exactly where it sits) and include the .zip archive at the same level. Think of it as doing two steps:

  1. Copy the directory recursively every individual file becomes its own R2 object.
  2. Copy the archive file a single object beside that folder tree.

Below are copy-paste-ready commands for the three most common tools (aws cli, wrangler, and rclone). Use whichever youre most comfortable with.

0. Pre-flight: define paths

# local base
export AETHERDEV=~/aetherdev
export MIXDIR="$AETHERDEV/media/mixtape_sessions/2025-04-24"

# remote bucket + prefix
export R2_BUCKET=one-bucket-to-rule-them-all
export R2_PREFIX=mixtape_sessions/2025-04-24
export R2_ENDPOINT=https://74b94b7ffc15701b.r2.cloudflarestorage.com

(Adjust R2_PREFIX if you want a different folder name in the bucket.)

1. Using AWS CLI

Make sure AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID / AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY are set for your R2 pair.

# 1 push the entire folder structure (un-zipped files)
aws --endpoint-url "$R2_ENDPOINT" \
    s3 cp "$MIXDIR/raw/" \
    "s3://$R2_BUCKET/$R2_PREFIX/raw/" \
    --recursive

# 2 push the .zip archive itself
aws --endpoint-url "$R2_ENDPOINT" \
    s3 cp "$MIXDIR/mixtape_sessions_2025-04-24.zip" \
    "s3://$R2_BUCKET/$R2_PREFIX/mixtape_sessions_2025-04-24.zip"

2. Using Wrangler v3+

# 1 recursively upload the raw folder
wrangler r2 object put --recursive \
  "$MIXDIR/raw" \
  --r2-bucket "$R2_BUCKET" \
  --key "$R2_PREFIX/raw"

# 2 upload the zip
wrangler r2 object put \
  "$MIXDIR/mixtape_sessions_2025-04-24.zip" \
  --r2-bucket "$R2_BUCKET" \
  --key "$R2_PREFIX/mixtape_sessions_2025-04-24.zip"

(Wrangler auto-detects your account from wrangler.toml or env vars.)

3. Using rclone

# R2 remote configured as 'cf' in rclone.conf
rclone copy "$MIXDIR/raw"   cf:"$R2_BUCKET/$R2_PREFIX/raw"
rclone copy "$MIXDIR/mixtape_sessions_2025-04-24.zip" \
            cf:"$R2_BUCKET/$R2_PREFIX/"

What git lfs track "*.zip" and .gitattributes do

Piece Purpose Why you need it
Git LFS (Large File Storage) An official Git extension that keeps large/binary files (audio, video, ZIPs, PSDs, etc.) out of normal Git history and stores them on a separate object server (still inside GitHub). Prevents your repo from ballooning; avoids GitHubs 100 MB per-file hard limit and keeps clone/fetch fast.
git lfs track "*.zip" Tells Git LFS to manage all files that match *.zip going forward. Git writes a rule to .gitattributes. Every time you git add a ZIP, Git stores a tiny pointer in the repo and shunts the real binary to LFS storage.
.gitattributes A config file in your repo that records which patterns are handled by LFS (and other text/binary rules). Needs to be version-controlled so everyone who clones the repo automatically uses the same LFS rules.

One-time setup (per machine)

# macOS (Homebrew)
brew install git-lfs
git lfs install      # sets up your global hooks

(Run git lfs install once; safe to repeatit just ensures hooks are in place.)

How to apply it in your repo

cd ~/aetherdev          # or the root of your repo

# 1  Tell LFS to track all future ZIPs
git lfs track "*.zip"

# 2  Stage the .gitattributes file that was just created/modified
git add .gitattributes

# 3  Commit the rule so teammates & CI pick it up
git commit -m "chore: track .zip files with Git LFS"

After this you can git add mixtape_sessions_2025-04-24.zip as usualthe files content goes to LFS storage, while the repo only holds a tiny pointer (< 1 KB).

What happens on GitHub

  • When you push, GitHub stores the ZIP in its LFS blob store.
  • Anyone who clones the repo (with Git LFS installed) automatically fetches the real ZIP.
  • Without LFS, theyd just see the pointer file and can use git lfs pull later.

TL;DR
git lfs track "*.zip" adds a rule to .gitattributes so ZIPs stay out of normal Git history.
Then you stage & commit .gitattributes like any other file to lock the rule in for good.

Your album-level master SKU should follow the exact same pattern as your individual tracks, but use 00 as the track-number placeholder. For Behold A Pale Horse, that means:

  • Master Album SKU: 
    HAWK-BAP-00

Why 00?

  • All your digital releases use the format HAWK-<AlbumCode>-<Track#> (e.g. HAWK-BAP-01 for Warning Shots, HAWK-BAP-02 for Behold A Pale Horse, through HAWK-BAP-11).
  • Reserving 00 lets you have a single, unambiguous identifier for the entire album package (in your case, the compiled .md file).

How to reference in your .md

At the top of your behold-a-pale-horse.md (or whatever you name it), you can include:

---
album: Behold A Pale Horse
sku: HAWK-BAP-00
tracks:
  - title: Warning Shots
    sku: HAWK-BAP-01
    link: ./01_warning_shots.md
  - title: Behold A Pale Horse
    sku: HAWK-BAP-02
    link: ./02_behold_a_pale_horse.md
  - title: Kamikaze
    sku: HAWK-BAP-03
    link: ./03_kamikaze.md
  # and so on through HAWK-BAP-11
---

That way:

  1. HAWK-BAP-00 clearly denotes the whole album.
  2. Each song stays linked to its own SKU and file.
